    "profile": "Born: December 10, 1908 (Avignon, France).\r\nDied: April 27, 1992.\r\n\r\nOlivier Messiaen was a French composer, organist, and ornithologist, one of the major composers of the 20th century.\r\n\r\nHe studied at the Paris Conservatoire (1919-1930) taught by [a833986], [a1598554] and [a962968] among others. He was eventually appointed as a professor at the Paris Conservatoire (1941-1978) while also serving as organist at [l336997]. It is apparent from his first published work of the eight Preludes for piano (1929), that he was using his own modal system, with its strong flavouring of tritones, diminished 7ths and augmented triads. During the 1930's he added a taste for rhythmic irregularity and for the rapid changing of intense colours, in both orchestral and organ works. Most of his compositions were explicitly religious and divided between characteristic styles of extremely slow meditation, bounding dance and the objective unfolding of arithmetical systems. They include the orchestral L'ascens",
